<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="121" pageId="8" pageNumber="120" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1415,2016]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,608]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="121" pageId="8" pageNumber="120">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1955,1980]" pageId="8" pageNumber="120">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species belongs to the ' 
<taxonomicName box="[666,797,1955,1980]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="8" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westerlundi">
<emphasis box="[666,797,1955,1980]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="120">westerlundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
' group. 
<emphasis box="[892,990,1955,1980]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="120">V. l a r i c i s</emphasis>
was briefly redescribed based on type specimens (Potapov 2001), concluding that it differed from 
<taxonomicName box="[846,1008,1991,2016]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="8" pageNumber="120" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westerlundi">
<emphasis box="[846,1008,1991,2016]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="120">V. westerlundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by darker and uniform pigmentation (
<figureCitation box="[159,244,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1482,1503]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,270,1457]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1460]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 28. Coloration of Buryatian species of Vertagopus: 25 – 26, V. ceratus sp. nov., populations from Barguzin Range (25) and Balan-Tamur Range (26); 27, V. asiaticus sp. nov.; 28, V. laricis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3099124/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) and fewer chaetae on ventral side of Th.III (Martynova 1979, Potapov 2001). According to our new observations, the dens of 
<emphasis box="[441,537,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. l a r i c i s</emphasis>
always has more than 24 anterior chaetae, also in type specimens (20–23 ones were incorrectly indicated in first description), the dens normally has 9 chaetae on the posterior side (3 basal and 3+3 
<emphasis box="[202,260,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">di-de</emphasis>
), furca as long as or longer than antennae (1.0–1.1), macrochaetae ca. 4 times longer than inner edge of the claw. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName box="[407,569,295,320]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westerlundi">
<emphasis box="[407,569,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. westerlundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 19–23 (rarely 25) anterior and 2+2 (more rarely 3+2) 
<emphasis box="[1268,1326,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">di-de</emphasis>
posterior chaetae on dens, furca shorter than antennae (0.7–0.9), macrochaetae ca. 3 times longer than inner edge of the claw. Habitus of 
<taxonomicName box="[275,375,367,392]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laricis">
<emphasis box="[275,375,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. laricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[428,587,367,392]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westerlundi">
<emphasis box="[428,587,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. westerlundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are given in 
<figureCitation box="[733,902,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 23 – 24" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1354,1375]" captionTargetBox="[202,1391,522,1322]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[195,1392,517,1333]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 23 – 24. Appearance and macrochaetotaxy of V. laricis (23) and V. westerlundi (24)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3099116/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Figs 23 and 24</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">
The last two abdominal segments are fused in 
<taxonomicName box="[719,818,404,429]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laricis">
<emphasis box="[719,818,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. laricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(vs. separated in 
<taxonomicName box="[1015,1173,404,429]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westerlundi">
<emphasis box="[1015,1173,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. westerlundi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). With this character 
<taxonomicName class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laricis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. laricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a unique member of the genus and is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Handschin. Other" authorityName="Handschin. Other" box="[780,1140,439,464]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Pseudisotoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[780,937,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Pseudisotoma</emphasis>
Handschin. Other
</taxonomicName>
principal characters of the species (11 chaetae in apical tibiotarsal whorl, quadridentate mucro) indicate the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1130,1256,477,500]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1130,1256,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Vertagopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="121" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,608]" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,512,511,536]" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Distribution and ecology.</emphasis>
Inner areas of the eastern Asia including Mongolia and several surrounding territories of Eastern Siberia and China (
<figureCitation box="[604,688,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1498,1519]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,207,1470]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,195,1476]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 29. Records of of three species of Vertagopus occurring in Buryat Republic. For V. l ar i c i s the papers of Martynova (1975), Dunger (1982), Stebaeva &amp; Sedelnikova (1999), Stebaeva et al. (2001), and Gulgenova (2012) were also used." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/269181/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). It is a rather common species in the south and centre of Buryatia. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,250,583,608]" class="Entognatha" family="Isotomidae" genus="Vertagopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Collembola" pageId="9" pageNumber="121" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laricis">
<emphasis box="[151,250,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="121">V. laricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
prefers xeric sites and inhabits coniferous litter of dry forests and sparse vegetation on exposed objects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
